### (1) **Translation of the Story into English**

**Original Passage (from 荀子, *Xunzi*):**

魏武侯謀事而當，群臣莫能逮，退朝而有喜色。吳起進曰：「亦嘗有以楚莊王之語，聞於左右者乎？」武侯曰：「楚莊王之語何如？」吳起對曰：「楚莊王謀事而當，群臣莫能逮，退朝而有憂色。申公巫臣進問曰：『王朝而有憂色，何也？』莊王曰：『不穀謀事而當，群臣莫能逮，是以憂也。其在中蘬之言也，曰：「諸侯自為得師者王，得友者霸，得疑者存，自為謀而莫己若者亡。」今以不穀之不肖，而群臣莫能逮，吾國幾於亡乎！是以憂也。』楚莊王以憂，而君以喜。」武侯逡巡再拜曰：「天使夫子振寡人之過也。」

**English Translation:**

Duke Wu of Wei made decisions wisely, and none of his ministers could match him. After court, he wore a pleased expression. Wu Qi (the famous general and statesman) approached and said: "Have you ever heard of what King Zhuang of Chu said to his attendants?"

Duke Wu asked: "What did King Zhuang of Chu say?"

Wu Qi replied: "King Zhuang of Chu also made wise decisions, and none of his ministers could match him. But after court, he wore a worried expression. Shen Gong Wuchen approached and asked: 'Your Majesty, you seem troubled after court. Why is that?'

King Zhuang said: 'I have made good decisions, and none of my ministers can match me. That is why I am worried. There is a saying from Zhong Xiong: "A prince who believes he has found a teacher will become a king; one who finds an equal will become a hegemon; one who faces opposition may still survive; but one who believes no one is as wise as himself will perish." Now, I am not virtuous, yet none of my ministers can match me. Is my country not nearly doomed to ruin? That is why I am worried.'

King Zhuang of Chu was worried, but you, my lord, are pleased."

Duke Wu hesitated for a moment, then bowed twice and said: "Heaven has sent you, Master, to correct my mistake."

